1. Introduction
The introduction presents an overview to assist the reader in understanding how this Software Requirements Specification (SRS) is organized and how to use it. This document covers all functional and non-functional requirements for the Student Internship Portal developed at The Islamia University of Bahawalpur, Department of Information Technology.

1.1 Purpose
The purpose of this Software Requirements Specification (SRS) document is to provide a complete and detailed description of the requirements for the Student Internship Portal. This document is intended for the development team, project supervisor, and academic evaluators. It describes the functional behavior, non-functional characteristics, constraints, and use case interactions of the system. This SRS serves as the foundational agreement between stakeholders and developers, ensuring that the final delivered system meets all defined objectives and expectations.

1.2 Scope
The Student Internship Portal is a web-based application developed using the Django framework (Python). The system is named Student Internship Portal (SIP). Its primary purpose is to provide a centralized digital platform that bridges the gap between students seeking internship opportunities and companies offering them. The portal eliminates manual, paper-based processes for internship management by digitizing the entire workflow.

The major features of the system include:
•	Student and company registration, authentication, and profile management
•	Internship opportunity posting and management by companies
•	Internship search, browsing, and application submission by students
•	Real-time application tracking and status updates
•	CV/resume upload functionality for students
•	Administrative panel for managing users, internships, and system activity
•	Automated notification system for application updates

The system does not include payment processing, video interview scheduling, or third-party HR system integrations in its current scope.

 
2. Overall Description
2.1 Product Perspective
The Student Internship Portal is an entirely new, standalone web application developed to serve the academic and professional needs of university students and industry companies. It is not a successor to an existing system but rather an original product designed to address the absence of a structured digital internship management process at The Islamia University of Bahawalpur.

The portal operates as a three-tier web application with a client browser layer, a Django-based application server layer, and a relational database layer. The system interacts with three primary actors: Students, Companies, and Administrators. It provides each actor with a dedicated dashboard and a tailored set of functionalities. The portal functions as a self-contained ecosystem where all internship-related activities — from posting to application to tracking — are handled within the platform.

2.2 Operating Environment
The Student Internship Portal shall operate within the following technical environment:

•	OE-1: The system shall operate correctly with the following web browsers: Google Chrome (version 90 and above), Mozilla Firefox (version 85 and above), Microsoft Edge (version 88 and above), and Apple Safari (version 13 and above).
•	OE-2: The server-side application shall run on a Linux-based operating system (Ubuntu 20.04 LTS or higher) with Python 3.9+ and the Django 4.x framework installed.
•	OE-3: The system shall use SQLite for development and PostgreSQL for production deployment as the relational database management system.
•	OE-4: The system shall be accessible over the internet through a standard HTTPS connection with a minimum bandwidth of 5 Mbps for optimal performance.
•	OE-5: The client machines accessing the portal shall require a modern web browser and internet connectivity. No additional software installation shall be required on the client side.
•	OE-6: The system shall be hosted on a web server (such as Gunicorn with Nginx) deployed on a cloud or on-premises server infrastructure.

2.3 Design and Implementation Constraints
The following constraints govern the design and implementation decisions of the Student Internship Portal:

•	CO-1: The system shall be developed exclusively using the Django web framework (Python) as the backend technology.
•	CO-2: The frontend interface shall be built using HTML5, CSS3, Bootstrap 5, and JavaScript. No other frontend JavaScript frameworks (e.g., React, Angular) shall be used in the initial version.
•	CO-3: The system shall use Django ORM (Object-Relational Mapping) for all database interactions. Raw SQL queries shall be avoided unless performance optimization demands them.
•	CO-4: All user-uploaded files (CVs, profile images) shall be stored in the server filesystem within Django's designated media directory and shall not exceed 5 MB per file.
•	CO-5: The system shall comply with standard web security practices including CSRF protection, input validation, and password hashing using Django's built-in authentication framework.
•	CO-6: The system shall be developed and delivered as a single deployable Django project, with modular applications organized by role (students, companies, admin).
•	CO-7: The project shall be version-controlled using Git, and the source code repository shall be maintained throughout the development lifecycle.

 
3. Requirement Identifying Technique
The primary technique used to identify and elicit the functional requirements of the Student Internship Portal is Use Case modeling. Use case analysis is the most effective technique for interactive, end-user-facing applications where multiple distinct actors interact with the system through well-defined workflows and scenarios. This technique allows the development team to identify system behavior from the user's perspective and derive precise functional requirements from actor-system interactions.

In this project, requirements were gathered through the following complementary techniques:

•	Use Case Analysis: Identifying all actors (Student, Company, Admin) and mapping their interactions with the system through structured use cases.
•	Stakeholder Interviews: Informal discussions with students and faculty members to understand expectations regarding internship searching and application processes.
•	Document Analysis: Review of existing academic portal structures and internship management systems to identify standard features and common workflows.
•	Observation: Studying manual internship processes at the university level to understand pain points that the digital system must address.

3.1 Use Case Diagram
The following Use Case Diagram illustrates all major interactions between the three primary actors — Student, Company, and Admin — and the Student Internship Portal system. The diagram was developed following UML standards and depicts functional boundaries, actor roles, and the include relationships between use cases.

 
Figure 1: Use Case Diagram – Student Internship Portal

As illustrated in Figure 1, the system encompasses three distinct actors and their respective use cases:

•	Student Actor: Interacts with the system through Register/Login (which includes Authenticate User), Create/Update Profile (which includes Authenticate User), Upload CV (which includes Authenticate User), Search Internships, Apply for Internship (which extends to View Internship Details), and Track Application Status.
•	Company Actor: Interacts with the system through Register/Login (which includes Authenticate User), Create Company Profile, Post Internship, and Manage Applications (Received).
