3.2 Use Case Description
The following section provides detailed descriptions for each major use case identified in the Use Case Diagram. Each use case is described using a standardized template including actors, description, trigger, preconditions, postconditions, normal flow, alternative flows, exceptions, business rules, and assumptions.

Use Case UC-1: Register / Login

Use Case ID:	UC-1
Use Case Name:	Register / Login
Actors:	Primary Actor: Student or Company Secondary Actor: Authentication System
Description:	A Student or Company user accesses the portal to create a new account or log into an existing account. Upon successful authentication, the user is redirected to their respective dashboard.
Trigger:	The user navigates to the portal and selects 'Register' or 'Login' from the homepage.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: The user must have access to the internet and a supported web browser. PRE-2: For login, the user must already have a registered account.
Postconditions:	POST-1: The user is authenticated and granted access to the system. POST-2: A session token is created and maintained for the user's current session.
Normal Flow:	1. User navigates to the portal homepage. 2. User selects 'Register' or 'Login'. 3. User enters required credentials (email, password; registration includes additional details). 4. System validates input and credentials. 5. System creates or verifies the user account. 6. User is redirected to the appropriate dashboard.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1 (Forgot Password): User selects 'Forgot Password', enters registered email, receives a password reset link, and resets password.
Exceptions:	E-1: Invalid credentials – system displays an error message and prompts re-entry. E-2: Duplicate email during registration – system informs the user the account already exists.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Passwords must be at least 8 characters and include at least one number. BR-2: Email addresses must be unique across the system.
Assumptions:	1. Users provide valid and accurate information during registration.

Use Case UC-2: Create / Update Profile

Use Case ID:	UC-2
Use Case Name:	Create / Update Profile
Actors:	Primary Actor: Student Secondary Actor: Authentication System
Description:	An authenticated Student creates or updates their personal profile, including academic information, skills, and contact details. This use case includes the Authenticate User use case.
Trigger:	Student navigates to the 'My Profile' section after logging in.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Student is logged into the system. PRE-2: Authentication has been completed successfully.
Postconditions:	POST-1: Student profile is saved/updated in the database. POST-2: Updated profile is visible to companies and administrators.
Normal Flow:	1. Student logs into the system. 2. Student navigates to the Profile section. 3. Student enters or updates personal, academic, and skills information. 4. Student submits the form. 5. System validates and saves the data. 6. System displays a confirmation message.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Student cancels the update – system discards changes and returns to the dashboard.
Exceptions:	E-1: Required fields left blank – system highlights missing fields and prompts completion. E-2: Invalid data format entered – system displays an appropriate validation message.
Business Rules:	BR-1: All mandatory profile fields must be completed before the student can apply for internships.
Assumptions:	1. Students have accurate academic and personal information to provide.

Use Case UC-3: Upload CV

Use Case ID:	UC-3
Use Case Name:	Upload CV
Actors:	Primary Actor: Student Secondary Actor: File Storage System
Description:	An authenticated Student uploads their Curriculum Vitae (CV) in PDF or DOCX format to the portal. The uploaded CV is stored securely and linked to the student's profile for companies to view.
Trigger:	Student selects the 'Upload CV' option from their profile or dashboard.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Student is logged into the system. PRE-2: Student profile has been created.
Postconditions:	POST-1: CV file is stored in the system's media directory. POST-2: CV is linked to the student's profile and available for application submissions.
Normal Flow:	1. Student navigates to the CV upload section. 2. Student selects a file from their local device. 3. System validates the file type (PDF/DOCX) and size (max 5 MB). 4. System uploads and stores the file. 5. System confirms successful upload.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Student replaces an existing CV – system overwrites the old file with the new upload.
Exceptions:	E-1: File exceeds 5 MB – system displays an error message. E-2: Unsupported file format – system rejects the file and prompts for a valid format.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Only PDF and DOCX file formats are accepted. BR-2: Maximum CV file size is 5 MB.
Assumptions:	1. Students have a prepared, up-to-date CV in digital format.

 
Use Case UC-4: Post Internship

Use Case ID:	UC-4
Use Case Name:	Post Internship
Actors:	Primary Actor: Company Secondary Actor: Authentication System
Description:	An authenticated Company representative posts a new internship opportunity on the portal, specifying details such as role title, description, required skills, duration, location, and application deadline.
Trigger:	Company selects 'Post Internship' from their company dashboard.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Company is logged into the system. PRE-2: Company profile has been created and verified.
Postconditions:	POST-1: Internship posting is saved to the database. POST-2: Internship is listed publicly and searchable by students.
Normal Flow:	1. Company navigates to 'Post Internship'. 2. Company fills in all required internship details. 3. System validates input fields. 4. System saves the internship record. 5. System confirms posting and displays the listing.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Company saves draft – internship is saved but not published publicly.
Exceptions:	E-1: Required fields incomplete – system highlights missing fields. E-2: Invalid deadline (past date) – system rejects the entry.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Application deadline must be a future date. BR-2: Internship duration must be specified in weeks or months.
Assumptions:	1. Company representatives provide accurate and complete internship information.

Use Case UC-5: Apply for Internship

Use Case ID:	UC-5
Use Case Name:	Apply for Internship
Actors:	Primary Actor: Student Secondary Actor: Notification System
Description:	An authenticated Student searches for and applies for an available internship. The application process includes viewing internship details and submitting an application, which triggers a notification to the company.
Trigger:	Student selects 'Apply' on a specific internship listing.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Student is logged in. PRE-2: Student profile is complete and CV has been uploaded. PRE-3: Internship application deadline has not passed.
Postconditions:	POST-1: Application record is stored in the database. POST-2: Application status is set to 'Pending'. POST-3: Company receives a notification of the new application.
Normal Flow:	1. Student browses or searches for internships. 2. Student selects an internship to view details. 3. Student clicks 'Apply'. 4. System confirms profile and CV are complete. 5. Student submits application. 6. System saves application and sends notification to the company. 7. System displays confirmation to the student.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Student has already applied – system informs the student and prevents duplicate application.
Exceptions:	E-1: Incomplete profile or missing CV – system prompts student to complete before applying. E-2: Application deadline passed – system disables the Apply button.
Business Rules:	BR-1: A student may apply to each internship only once. BR-2: Applications can only be submitted before the listed deadline.
Assumptions:	1. Students read the internship details before applying.

Use Case UC-6: Manage Applications (Company)

Use Case ID:	UC-6
Use Case Name:	Manage Applications (Received)
Actors:	Primary Actor: Company Secondary Actor: Notification System
Description:	A Company representative reviews all applications received for their posted internships, views student profiles and CVs, and updates the application status (Accepted, Rejected, or Shortlisted).
Trigger:	Company navigates to 'Manage Applications' from the dashboard.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Company is logged in. PRE-2: Company has at least one active internship posting with received applications.
Postconditions:	POST-1: Application status is updated in the database. POST-2: Student receives a notification regarding the status change.
Normal Flow:	1. Company navigates to the Applications section. 2. System displays a list of all received applications. 3. Company selects an application to review. 4. Company views student profile and CV. 5. Company updates the application status. 6. System saves the status and notifies the student.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Company filters applications by internship or status for easier management.
Exceptions:	E-1: No applications received – system displays an informational message.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Only the company that posted the internship can manage its applications.
Assumptions:	1. Company representatives evaluate applications fairly and promptly.

 
Use Case UC-7: Track Application Status

Use Case ID:	UC-7
Use Case Name:	Track Application Status
Actors:	Primary Actor: Student Secondary Actor: Notification System
Description:	An authenticated Student monitors the current status of all submitted internship applications from their dashboard. The system displays real-time status updates such as Pending, Shortlisted, Accepted, or Rejected.
Trigger:	Student navigates to 'My Applications' from the student dashboard.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Student is logged in. PRE-2: Student has submitted at least one application.
Postconditions:	POST-1: Student views the current status of all submitted applications.
Normal Flow:	1. Student navigates to 'My Applications'. 2. System retrieves and displays all applications with their current status. 3. Student reviews status updates.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Student clicks on an application to view detailed feedback or company response.
Exceptions:	E-1: No applications submitted – system displays 'No applications found' message.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Application status is only updated by the company or administrator.
Assumptions:	1. Status updates are reflected in real-time upon company action.

Use Case UC-8: Admin – Manage Users

Use Case ID:	UC-8
Use Case Name:	Manage Users
Actors:	Primary Actor: Admin
Description:	The system administrator manages all registered user accounts on the portal, including viewing user details, activating or deactivating accounts, and removing inappropriate or duplicate accounts.
Trigger:	Admin navigates to the User Management section of the admin panel.
Preconditions:	PRE-1: Admin is authenticated with administrator-level privileges.
Postconditions:	POST-1: User account is activated, deactivated, or deleted as per admin action. POST-2: Changes are reflected immediately in the system.
Normal Flow:	1. Admin logs into the admin panel. 2. Admin navigates to 'Manage Users'. 3. System displays a list of all registered users. 4. Admin selects a user and performs the required action. 5. System updates the user status accordingly.
Alternative Flows:	AF-1: Admin searches for a specific user by name or email.
Exceptions:	E-1: Attempt to delete own admin account – system prevents the action.
Business Rules:	BR-1: Only users with Admin role can access the user management panel.
Assumptions:	1. The admin acts in accordance with the university's data management policies.

 
